"Solomon S., Rosenlof K.H., Portmann R.W., Daniel J.S., Davis S.M., Sanford T.J., Plattner G.-K.","Contributions of stratospheric water vapor to decadal changes in the rate of global warming",2010,"Science","327","5970",,"1219","1223",,,10.1126/science.1182488,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77749264571&partnerID=40&md5=d41ee64ebe449f377073e6eae4b32892","National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States; Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO, United States; Climate and Environmental Physics, Physics Institute, University of Bern, Sidlerstrasse 5, 3012 Bern, Switzerland","Solomon, S., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States; Rosenlof, K.H., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States; Portmann, R.W., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States; Daniel, J.S., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States; Davis, S.M., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO, United States; Sanford, T.J., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Earth System Research Laboratory, Chemical Sciences Division, Boulder, CO, United States, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO, United States; Plattner, G.-K., Climate and Environmental Physics, Physics Institute, University of Bern, Sidlerstrasse 5, 3012 Bern, Switzerland","Stratospheric water vapor concentrations decreased by about 10% after the year 2000. Mere we show that this acted to slow the rate of increase in global surface temperature over 2000-2009 by about 25% compared to that which would have occurred due only to carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases. More limited data suggest that stratospheric water vapor probably increased between 1980 and 2000, which would have enhanced the decadal rate of surface warming during the 1990s by about 30% as compared to estimates neglecting this change. These findings show that stratospheric water vapor is an important driver of decadal global surface climate change.",,"carbon dioxide; carbon dioxide; climate change; decadal variation; global warming; greenhouse gas; stratosphere; surface temperature; trend analysis; water vapor; article; climate change; controlled study; environmental temperature; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; human; oxidation; priority journal; stratosphere; warming; water vapor",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4",,,,"(2007) The Physical Science Basis, Contribution of Working Group i to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , IPCC, Climate Change 2007: S. Solomon et al., Eds. Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge; Easterling, D.R., Wehner, F.M., (2009) Geophys. Res. Lett., 36, pp. L08706; De Forster, P.M.S., Shine, K.P., (1999) Geophys. Res. Lett., 26, p. 3309; Smith, C.A., Haigh, J.D., Toumi, R., (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28, p. 179; Shindell, D.T., (2001) Geophys. Res. Lea., 28, p. 1551; Trenberth, K.E., Fasullo, J., Smith, L., (2005) Clim. Dyn., 24, p. 741; Dessler, A.E., Zhang, Z., Yang, P., (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L20704; Mote, P.W., (1996) J. Geophys. Res., 101 (D2), p. 3989; Cordera, E.C., Forster, P.M., (2006) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 6, p. 5369; Gettleman, A., (2009) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 9, p. 1621; Garcia, R.R., Marsh, D.R., Kinnison, D